{"info": {"author": "Tom Stokes, Tom Egan", "author_email": "tom@tomegan.tech", "bugtrack_url": null, "classifiers": ["Development Status :: 5 - Production/Stable", "Intended Audience :: Developers", "License :: OSI Approved :: MIT License", "Operating System :: POSIX :: Linux", "Programming Language :: Python :: 2.7", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3", "Topic :: Software Development :: Embedded Systems"], "description": "# python3-spi\n\nPython 3.x interface for SPI communications using Linux spidev\n\nThis is a fork of https://github.com/tomstokes/python-spi which seems to be abandoned with the python 3 compatibility patch proposed by Tom Egan applied.\n\n## Features\n\n- Pure Python implementation. No C module to compile.\n- Supports half-duplex reads and writes as well as full-duplex transfers.\n- Exposes all available spidev interface options as properties.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- spidev enabled in the kernel and (if necessary) the device tree.\n- Write permissions to the /dev/spidevN.N device.\n  - Some distributions have an 'spi' group for this purpose. If available, add this group to the user account and ensure the spidev device is group-writeable.\n  - If no 'spi' group exists, a udev rule can be created to set the permissions of the spidev device.\n  - As a last resort, running the python script as root should allow access to the spidev. **Note** This is not recommended. Use the 'spi' group or udev rules whenever possible.\n\n## Example\n```python3\nimport spi\nspi = SPI(\"/dev/spidev1.0\")\nspi.mode = SPI.MODE_0\nspi.bits_per_word = 8\nspi.speed = 500000\nreceived = spi.transfer([0x11, 0x22, 0xFF])\nspi.write([0x12, 0x34, 0xAB, 0xCD])\nreceived = spi.read(10)\n```\n\n\n", "description_content_type": "text/markdown", "docs_url": null, "download_url": "", "downloads": {"last_day": -1, "last_month": -1, "last_week": -1}, "home_page": "https://github.com/tkegan/python-spi", "keywords": "", "license": "MIT", "maintainer": "", "maintainer_email": "", "name": "python3-spi", "package_url": "https://pypi.org/project/python3-spi/", "platform": "", "project_url": "https://pypi.org/project/python3-spi/", "project_urls": {"Homepage": "https://github.com/tkegan/python-spi"}, "release_url": "https://pypi.org/project/python3-spi/0.3.1/", "requires_dist": null, "requires_python": ">=2.7, !=3.0.*, <4", "summary": "Python interface for SPI communications", "version": "0.3.1", "yanked": false, "html_description": "<div class=\"project-description\">\n            <h1>python3-spi</h1>\n<p>Python 3.x interface for SPI communications using Linux spidev</p>\n<p>This is a fork of <a href=\"https://github.com/tomstokes/python-spi\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://github.com/tomstokes/python-spi</a> which seems to be abandoned with the python 3 compatibility patch proposed by Tom Egan applied.</p>\n<h2>Features</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Pure Python implementation. No C module to compile.</li>\n<li>Supports half-duplex reads and writes as well as full-duplex transfers.</li>\n<li>Exposes all available spidev interface options as properties.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Requirements</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>spidev enabled in the kernel and (if necessary) the device tree.</li>\n<li>Write permissions to the /dev/spidevN.N device.\n<ul>\n<li>Some distributions have an 'spi' group for this purpose. If available, add this group to the user account and ensure the spidev device is group-writeable.</li>\n<li>If no 'spi' group exists, a udev rule can be created to set the permissions of the spidev device.</li>\n<li>As a last resort, running the python script as root should allow access to the spidev. <strong>Note</strong> This is not recommended. Use the 'spi' group or udev rules whenever possible.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Example</h2>\n<pre><span class=\"kn\">import</span> <span class=\"nn\">spi</span>\n<span class=\"n\">spi</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">SPI</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"s2\">\"/dev/spidev1.0\"</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"n\">spi</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">mode</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">SPI</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">MODE_0</span>\n<span class=\"n\">spi</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">bits_per_word</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"mi\">8</span>\n<span class=\"n\">spi</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">speed</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"mi\">500000</span>\n<span class=\"n\">received</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">spi</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">transfer</span><span class=\"p\">([</span><span class=\"mh\">0x11</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"mh\">0x22</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"mh\">0xFF</span><span class=\"p\">])</span>\n<span class=\"n\">spi</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">write</span><span class=\"p\">([</span><span class=\"mh\">0x12</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"mh\">0x34</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"mh\">0xAB</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"mh\">0xCD</span><span class=\"p\">])</span>\n<span class=\"n\">received</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">spi</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">read</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"mi\">10</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n</pre>\n\n          </div>"}, "last_serial": 6703933, "releases": {"0.3.0": [{"comment_text": "", "digests": {"md5": "69b81c318978e3be2382106057e3c56f", "sha256": "9c923df3ba10e800b9e7adfe986c0e99955891c8edd89746d5855559410336b5"}, "downloads": -1, "filename": "python3_spi-0.3.0-py3-none-any.whl", "has_sig": false, "md5_digest": "69b81c318978e3be2382106057e3c56f", "packagetype": "bdist_wheel", "python_version": "py3", "requires_python": null, "size": 6663, "upload_time": "2020-02-25T16:02:37", "upload_time_iso_8601": "2020-02-25T16:02:37.847130Z", "url": "https://files.pythonhosted.or